🎯 What is Django Template Inheritance?

Django project il common HTML code (Navbar, Footer, CSS links, JavaScript imports, Bootstrap etc.) oro page-ilum repeat cheyyathe reuse cheyyan vendi aanu Template Inheritance use cheyyunnath.

Basically, nammal oru base template create cheyyum, baki ella pages um athine inherit cheyyum.

👉 Django-yile DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle implement cheyyanulla oru important feature aanu.

---

🧠 Simple Explanation

Nammal oru ecommerce website build cheyyunnu enn karuthuka.

Pages:

- Home Page
- Store Page
- Product Detail Page
- Cart Page

Ee ella pages-ilum common ayi ullath:

- Navbar
- Footer
- CSS Files
- JavaScript Files

Inheritance illenkil ee code ella page-ilum copy-paste cheyyendi varum.

Template Inheritance use cheythal common code oru single file-il vechu manage cheyyam.

---

🔄 How it works internally

1. Create a Base Template

Example: "base.html"

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>My Store</title>
</head>
<body>

    <nav>
        Navbar
    </nav>

    {% block content %}
    {% endblock %}

    <footer>
        Footer
    </footer>

</body>
</html>

---

2. Create a Child Template

Example: "home.html"

{% extends 'base.html' %}

{% block content %}
<h1>Welcome to Home Page</h1>
{% endblock %}

---

3. Django Combines Both Templates

When the page is rendered:

- Base template is loaded first.
- Child template content is inserted into the matching block.

---

4. Final Output in Browser

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>My Store</title>
</head>
<body>

    <nav>
        Navbar
    </nav>

    <h1>Welcome to Home Page</h1>

    <footer>
        Footer
    </footer>

</body>
</html>

---

💡 Why do we need Template Inheritance?

Without Template Inheritance:

❌ Repeated Navbar code

❌ Repeated Footer code

❌ Repeated CSS and JavaScript imports

❌ Difficult maintenance

With Template Inheritance:

✔ Reusable layout

✔ Less code duplication

✔ Easy maintenance

✔ Clean project structure

✔ Better scalability

---

🚀 Where is it used?

- Ecommerce Websites
- Blog Websites
- Company Websites
- Portfolio Websites
- Learning Management Systems

Almost every Django project uses Template Inheritance.

---

⚡ Summary

Django Template Inheritance allows multiple pages to share a common HTML structure using a base template. Instead of repeating the same layout code in every page, common elements such as Navbar, Footer, CSS, and JavaScript imports are defined once in a base template and reused across the project.

This makes the application cleaner, easier to maintain, and follows the DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle.
